<item>
 <title>Learning to Scribe: Lessons from Troubadours and Other Performers</title>
 <link>https://trobar-test.sites.stanford.edu/learning-scribe-lessons-troubadours-and-other-performers</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot; property=&quot;content:encoded&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;Statement of intent: Documentary on my process of trying to transcribe a modern-day version of Marcabru&#039;s &quot;Pax in Nomine Domini&quot; with many twists.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This project aims to explore the idea of performance by examining past and current modes of the documentation process. With troubadours and a “Pax in Nomine Domini” manuscript as my guides, I wished to emulate the very style of transcription used by scribes in medieval times. This mini “documentary” highlights the journey that took place after this original idea grew into an in depth look at the nature of human performers and audiences. Several personal reflections, interviews, and Stanford performances later, I have come to see that there are many ties between performers past and present, and that my idea of a performance will never be the same. Underneath it all is the initial goal of transcribing, which surprises me at the end when I realize how much is buried beneath a simple desire to recreate something from the past.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This video is on vimeo.com, and if it asks for a password for the video, it is “troubadour” (all lowercase). Here is the link in case the embedding didn&#039;t work for this project post: &lt;a href=&quot;http://vimeo.com/90020835&quot;&gt;http://vimeo.com/90020835&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-course field-type-entityreference field-label-above&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-label&quot;&gt;Course:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;Songs of Love and War: Gender, Crusade, Politics (Winter 2014)&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-inline clearfix&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-label&quot;&gt;Tags:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/tags/video&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;video&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item odd&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/tags/transcription&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;transcription&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/tags/documentary&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;documentary&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-project-type field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-inline clearfix&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-label&quot;&gt;Project type:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;/project-type/creative-work&quot; typeof=&quot;skos:Concept&quot; property=&quot;rdfs:label skos:prefLabel&quot; datatype=&quot;&quot;&gt;creative work&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
 <pubDate>Tue, 25 Mar 2014 07:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
 <dc:creator>Kim Grace McCabe</dc:creator>
 <guid isPermaLink="false">611 at https://trobar-test.sites.stanford.edu</guid>
